\subtree{
\title{Implementing Envelope Encryption with AWS KMS}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{Envelope encryption is a strategy where data is encrypted with a data encryption key (DEK), and the DEK itself is encrypted with a master key (KEK) managed by AWS KMS. This approach allows encrypting large volumes of data locally while keeping the master key secure in a hardware security module (HSM) managed by AWS. This skill covers implementing envelope encryption using AWS KMS GenerateDataKey API.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{When deploying or configuring implementing envelope encryption with aws kms capabilities in your environment}
\li{When establishing security controls aligned to compliance requirements}
\li{When building or improving security architecture for this domain}
\li{When conducting security assessments that require this implementation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Familiarity with cryptography concepts and tools}
\li{Access to a test or lab environment for safe execution}
\li{Python 3.8+ with required dependencies installed}
\li{Appropriate authorization for any testing activities}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Objectives}
\ul{
\li{Understand the envelope encryption pattern and its advantages}
\li{Generate data encryption keys using AWS KMS GenerateDataKey}
\li{Encrypt/decrypt data locally using DEKs}
\li{Store encrypted DEK alongside ciphertext}
\li{Implement key caching to reduce KMS API calls}
\li{Handle key rotation with automatic re-encryption}
\li{Implement multi-region encryption for disaster recovery}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\subtree{
\title{Envelope Encryption Flow}
\ol{
\li{Call \code{\startverb kms:GenerateDataKey\stopverb} to get plaintext DEK + encrypted DEK}
\li{Use plaintext DEK to encrypt data locally (AES-256-GCM)}
\li{Store encrypted DEK alongside ciphertext}
\li{Discard plaintext DEK from memory}
\li{For decryption: call \code{\startverb kms:Decrypt\stopverb} on encrypted DEK, then decrypt data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advantages Over Direct KMS Encryption}
\pre{\startverb
| Aspect | Direct KMS | Envelope Encryption |
|--------|-----------|-------------------|
| Max data size | 4 KB | Unlimited |
| Latency | Network round-trip per operation | Local encryption |
| Cost | $0.03/10,000 requests | Fewer KMS requests |
| Offline | Not possible | Yes (with cached DEKs) |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{KMS Key Types}
\ul{
\li{\strong{AWS Managed}: AWS creates and manages (\code{\startverb aws/s3\stopverb}, \code{\startverb aws/ebs\stopverb})}
\li{\strong{Customer Managed}: You create and manage policies}
\li{\strong{Custom Key Store}: Backed by CloudHSM cluster}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Security Considerations}
\ul{
\li{Never store plaintext DEK; only keep encrypted DEK}
\li{Use key policies to restrict who can call GenerateDataKey and Decrypt}
\li{Enable AWS CloudTrail logging for all KMS API calls}
\li{Implement key rotation (automatic annual rotation for CMKs)}
\li{Use encryption context for authenticated encryption metadata}
\li{Handle KMS throttling with exponential backoff}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Validation Criteria}
\ul{
\li{[ ] GenerateDataKey returns plaintext and encrypted DEK}
\li{[ ] Data encrypts correctly with plaintext DEK using AES-256-GCM}
\li{[ ] Encrypted DEK can be decrypted via KMS Decrypt API}
\li{[ ] Decrypted DEK recovers the original data}
\li{[ ] Plaintext DEK is wiped from memory after use}
\li{[ ] Encryption context is validated during decryption}
\li{[ ] Key rotation re-encrypts DEKs with new master key}
}
}
}